  "prompt": "What book would be best to start with to learn the mathematics of quantum mechanics?",
  "response": "For learning the mathematics of quantum mechanics, here are some recommended books at different levels:\n\nBeginner Level:\n1. \"Mathematical Methods in the Physical Sciences\" by Mary L. Boas\n- Comprehensive overview of mathematical techniques\n- Accessible introduction to mathematical methods used in physics\n\nIntermediate Level:\n2. \"Mathematical Tools for Physics\" by James Gilmore\n- Covers linear algebra, complex analysis, group theory\n- Specifically oriented towards physics applications\n\nAdvanced Undergraduate/Graduate Level:\n3. \"Linear Algebra and Its Applications\" by Gilbert Strang\n- Fundamental linear algebra, essential for quantum mechanics\n- Clear explanations of vector spaces and linear transformations\n\nQuantum Mechanics Specific Mathematics:\n4. \"Mathematical Foundations of Quantum Mechanics\" by John von Neumann\n- Classic text on mathematical foundations\n- More mathematically rigorous approach\n\nRecommended Progression:\n1. Start with Boas for foundational mathematical methods\n2. Study linear algebra (Strang)\n3. Move to Gilmore for physics-specific mathematical techniques\n4. Advanced students can then tackle von Neumann\n\nEach book offers different depth and perspective, so choose based on your current mathematical background and comfort level.",
